<text>Debye-Waller factor

Because there exists thermal motion, the atomic scattering factor in X-ray crystallography depends on the temperature. The thermal effect is described by the following equation:

fB=f*exp[-B*(sin(theta)/lambda)2]

where B is the Debye-Waller factor:

B=8pi2&lt;u2&gt;

Namely, B is proportional to the atomic mean square displacement. The Debye-Waller relation means that the atomic scattering power weakens when the temperature increases.

   
